The above table shows clearly that actual users who bought the games are most appreciative of Role-Playing(RPG), closely followed by Strategy and Fighting.

Opinion:

RPGs like Assassin's creed are by far the most popular games bought and played. It is of course one of the greatest RPG cum Strategy games released by Ubisoft on multiple platforms. It combines RPG, Adventure and Strategy. Call of Duty and Battlefield are by far the most popular shooters which are bought and played a lot.

The above table shows that Critics are most appreciative of Sports, followed by Strategy and Role-Playing(RPG) games.

Opinion:

There is clearly a shift in the scores of critics compared to users. Usually it is found that critics do not buy the games and the critic scores are largely based on online viewing of gameplays. Therefore a game that may be great when playing on your own might not be so appealing when gameplays are the mode of judgement.

In [18]:
def score_group(score):
    if score >= 90:
        return '90-100'
    elif score >= 80:
        return '80-89'
    elif score >= 70:
        return '70-79'
    elif score >= 60:
        return '60-69'
    elif score >= 50:
        return '50-59'
    else:
        return '0-49'
In [19]:
dfh = df
dfh['Score_Group'] = dfh['Critic_Score'].apply(lambda x: score_group(x))
In [20]:
def in_top(x):
    if x in pack:
        return x
    else:
        pass
def width(x):
    if x == 'Platform':
        return 14.4
    elif x == 'Developer':
        return 13.2
    elif x == 'Publisher':
        return 11.3
    elif x == 'Genre':
        return 13.6

def height(x):
    if x == 'Genre':
        return 8
    else:
        return 9

cols = ['Genre', 'Developer', 'Publisher', 'Platform']
for col in cols:
    pack = []
    top = dfh[['Name', col]].groupby([col]).count().sort_values('Name', ascending=False).reset_index()[:15]
    for x in top[col]:
        pack.append(x)
    dfh[col] = dfh[col].apply(lambda x: in_top(x))
    dfh_platform = dfh[[col, 'Score_Group', 'Global_players']].groupby([col, 'Score_Group']).median().reset_index().pivot(col, "Score_Group", "Global_players")
    plt.figure(figsize=(width(col), height(col)))
    sns.heatmap(dfh_platform, annot=True, fmt=".2g", linewidths=.5).set_title((' \n'+col+' vs. critic score (by median sales) \n'), fontsize=18)
    plt.ylabel('', fontsize=14)
    plt.xlabel('Score group \n', fontsize=12)
    pack = []
In [23]:
cols = ['Platform', 'Genre', 'Publisher', 'Developer', 'Rating']
for col in cols:
    uniques = df[col].value_counts().keys()
    uniques_dict = {}
    ct = 0
    for i in uniques:
        uniques_dict[i] = ct
        ct += 1

    for k, v in uniques_dict.items():
        df.loc[df[col] == k, col] = v

plt.show()

The relationship looks much clearer now. It's interesting how the slope gets steeper in the 80's. It seems once a game gets a high critic score, every additional point has a higher impact. Go big or go home, right?

Looks like critic scores will be a good feature for the prediction model in section 2.

Defining hits as those with sales above 1 million units¶

This will be the target in our prediction model, where we'll predict if a game will be a hit or not.

In [28]:
dfb = df[['Name','Platform','Genre','Publisher','Year_of_Release','Critic_Score','Global_players']]
dfb = dfb.dropna().reset_index(drop=True)
df2 = dfb[['Platform','Genre','Publisher','Year_of_Release','Critic_Score','Global_players']]
df2['Hit'] = df2['Global_players']
df2.drop('Global_players', axis=1, inplace=True)
In [29]:
def hit(sales):
    if sales >= 1:
        return 1
    else:
        return 0

df2['Hit'] = df2['Hit'].apply(lambda x: hit(x))

Let's graph the relationship between critic scores and VG hits using a 5% sample...

In [30]:
# Logistic regression plot with sample of the data
n = ceil(0.05 * len(df2['Hit']))
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,1, figsize=(12,5))
sns.regplot(x="Critic_Score", y="Hit", data=df2.sample(n=n),
            logistic=True, n_boot=500, y_jitter=.04, color="#75556c")
plt.show()

As expected, it seems hits are mostly found near high critic scores, while non-hits can vary in scores but don't have as strong of a presence in the high score ranges (as seen in the steepening regression curve near the 70's).
